Welsh elected representatives are dismayed by a proposal to replace their title with the name MWP (Member of the Welsh Parliament, Member of the Welsh Parliament).
This proposal stems from the proposed amendment to the name of the assembly, which would become the Welsh Parliament.
In the political sphere, members of the Assembly believe that this could be the subject of mockery.
A Labour elected official indicated that his group is concerned that the acronym "rhymes with Twp and Pwp".
For non-Wales readers: in Welsh, twp means stupid, and pwp means crotch.
According to one of its members, the Plaid Cymru (Wales Party) is not "satisfied" and has proposed other formulas.
The Conservative party would be "open" to a name change, but noted that between MWP and Muppet (marionette), the distance is narrow.
In this context, in Welsh, the letter w is pronounced as the letter u in English of the Yorkshire region.
The Assembly Committee, which is currently preparing the legislation introducing the change of name, has indicated that "the final decision on the name of the members of the Assembly belongs to the members of the Assembly".
The Government of Wales Act of 2017 gives the Welsh Assembly the power to change its name.
In June, the Commission published the results of a public consultation on the proposal to designate the House as the Welsh Parliament, which was widely supported.
On the question of the title of Members, the Commission favours Members of the Welsh Parliament (or WMP); however, a large majority of Welsh prefers MWP.
It seems that the members of the Assembly are making further suggestions, but the effort to reach consensus could prove to be a real puzzle for Elin Jones, the Speaker of the Assembly, who should submit a bill on name change in the coming weeks.
The reform legislation will include other changes concerning the functioning of the assembly, including rules on the exclusion of members and the design of the committee system.
Members of the Assembly will make the final decision on the name question during the debates on the bill.
