Greece, one of whose provinces is called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbour represents a right in its territory and vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
In June, both governments signed an agreement based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents claim that change would affect the ethical identity of the majority Slavic population of Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov announced that he would not vote in the referendum and that a boycott campaign had raised doubts about obtaining a minimum turnout of 50% required to validate the referendum.
