It has become clear that contrary opinions are no longer tolerated within the party. Each opinion is judged according to its acceptability by the party leaders.
It started shortly after Jeremy took power, and the colleagues with whom I thought I shared the same political vision began to expect me to turn over my jacket and take positions that were contrary to my convictions, whether on national security or on the EU internal market.
Every time I spoke publicly, and no matter what I said, followed an abusive tirade on social networks, calling for withdrawal, denouncing center policies, telling me that I should not be a party member.
And it's not just my experience.
Moreover, I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments addressed to me were of a political nature.
I am in admiration for the professionalism and determination of these colleagues, who face a flurry of sexist or racist remarks every day, but who do not give up their arms.
One of the most disappointing things in current policy is the normalization of different forms of abuse.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said the Labour Party should encourage a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer this large community and that the party is narrowing down as a result of motions of no confidence and changes to the rules of selection.
I've been given a lot of advice over the past two years: look down, not express my ideas so loud, and everything would go well.
But it's not to act like this that I do politics.
I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a schoolboy, because the negligence of Thatcher's government had caused the collapse of my classroom. Since then, I have wanted to work for better public services for those who need it most, whether as a local councillor or government minister.
I have never hidden my political ambitions, even in the last elections.
No one in Nottingham East could be disturbed by my political positions and my differences with the current party leaders.
All I would like to say to those who defended the motion on Friday is that the country is moving towards a Brexit that will affect homes, businesses and public services, and I don't really think this is the time to waste time and energy debating my loyalty to the party leader.
My only message is not for Nottingham Momentum, it is for my constituents, whether they are Labour or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise you that no threat of withdrawal or opportunism will prevent me from acting for the causes I defend, which are your interests to all of you.
