“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, blocked, hopes the court will re-open the way to the Pacific
Seamen patrol an armoured boat in Naval Headquarters La Paz.
Public buildings have a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to Amazonia, naval bases display the following motorcycle: "The sea is ours.
Recovering it is a duty."
Throughout Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still present, as is the desire to sail on the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades, because Bolivia is awaiting a decision by the International Court of Justice, which will be rendered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive result," explains Roberto Calzadilla, Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on a large screen throughout the country, hoping that the Hague Court will decide in favour of the Bolivian request. Bolivia hopes that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile will be obliged to negotiate the agreement of a sovereign passage to the ocean in Bolivia.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia (who is facing a controversial fight for re-election next year), also has much to say about the decision that will be made on Monday.
"We are so close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that there is little chance that the court will decide in favour of Chile, and that little would change, even in the event of a positive decision.
The United Nations body based in the Netherlands does not have the power to grant Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice rendered its decision six months after the last arguments showed that the case “was not complicated”, explains Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have even harmed it.
"The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," said Zárate.
Morales' belligerent rhetoric undermined all the Chilean goodwill that remained, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange views, but after that it will be very difficult to hold talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in the Hague, rejected the idea that the Court's decision-making was abnormally fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also challenged the fact that Morales - which so far remains one of the most popular presidents in Latin America - used the maritime problem as a political crutches.
"Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The Court's decision is an opportunity to see that we must get rid of the past."
