North Korea states that disarmament cannot be achieved unilaterally without confidence.
On Saturday, the North Korean Minister of Foreign Affairs told the United Nations that the maintenance of sanctions reinforced his distrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons in these circumstances.
At the annual General Assembly of the global organization, Ri Yong Ho claimed that North Korea had taken “important measures of goodwill” last year, such as putting an end to such measures as the cessation of nuclear testing and missiles, the dismantling of the nuclear test site and its commitment not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we see no corresponding response from the United States," he regretted.
In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear for our national security and, in such circumstances, we cannot be the first to disarm unilaterally."
While reiterating North Korea's well-known criticism of Washington's opposition to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it gradually took action, its statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the very first summit between an incumbent US president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work for a "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea seeks to officially end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has stated that Pyongyang must first renounce its nuclear weapons.
Washington also refused requests to relax severe international sanctions against North Korea.
The United States insists that North Korea proceed first with denuclearization and intensify pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve its objective in a coercive manner, even opposing the "Declaration of End of War"."
"Those who think these sanctions can make us rain don't know us.
The problem is that the maintenance of sanctions increases our mistrust."
Ri made no comment on the second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted in front of the United Nations by the US leader earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, and added: "If the party concerned with the issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a deadlock."
Nevertheless, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different from last year's, when he stated before the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles on North American territory after the "evil" President Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
Trump, who had threatened last year in front of the United Nations to "completely destroy" North Korea, did not miss praise this year for the courage with which Kim implemented disarmament measures, but added that much remained to be done and sanctions would not be lifted until North Korea disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump said no deadline had been set."It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn't matter," he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures adopted.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council last Thursday that: "The application of Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until complete, definitive and verified denuclearization."
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in order to stifle the financing of Pyongyang nuclear programmes and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met Ri on the margins of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare a second summit.
This year, Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang claiming that progress had been made but, in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced its "gangster methods".
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the United States took "equivalent measures".
He has, according to South Korean President, called for Trump's promised security assurances in Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: Students Take Rest Courses
This year, Harvard University has introduced a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and fights the growing machist tendency of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
One professor noted that most students at the best university in the world don't know how to take care of them
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is according to him the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him
In the end, a student approached me and said, "Why is this only said to me in the final year?"
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
First offered this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general director of health services at the university, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that the students were suffering from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The time of class consists of various interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing various objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not change students' behaviour instantly.
However, in our view, they have the right to know this information - just as you have the right to know what the health effects of smoking are," added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride in "spending a white night" still exists, and he adds that modern technology and growing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having sufficient and good quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep puts the brain into an inanition mode, making them permanently hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He claimed that this course had opened his eyes and had prompted him to insist that it be offered throughout the campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar program of study before joining the renowned institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students plan an alarm for both bedtime and waking, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and cause sleep disturbances.
