And now, a page from our Almanach "Sunday Morning": On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and THE TOURNE ACCOUNT...was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, Germany.
Geiger developed a method to detect and measure radioactivity; an invention that subsequently gave rise to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science since then, the Geiger meter has also become fundamental in pop culture, as can be seen in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", along with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two unlikely scientists:
A man: "What is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger meter, it's used to search for radioactive minerals, like uranium.
Thanks to these headphones, we can really hear the effects of atoms released into the minerals by radioactivity."
Evans: "Say, it's sure to jump right now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains.
A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to "detect" cancer cells
A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to "detect" cancer cells and kill them
As part of the treatment, the vaccine tells the immune system how to recognize cancer cells
This technique involves extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory.
They can then "detect" a protein that is common to many cancers, and are then re-injected
An experimental vaccine shows encouraging results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who received the vaccine, whose goal is to teach the immune system to recognize cancer cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method consists of extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory, so that they can detect the HER2 protein common to many cancers, and finally reinject them.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the American National Cancer Institute based in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results indicate that we have a very promising vaccine."
According to Professor Berzofsky, the HER2 protein "produces an increase in several types of cancer", including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancer.
A similar approach, which involves taking immune cells to "learn" them to target cancer cells, has proven itself in the treatment of a type of leukemia.
