Germany's new warship still postponed
According to local media, the German Navy's new frigate should have been put into service in 2014 to replace the aging warships dating back to the Cold War, but it will not be in service until at least next year due to faulty systems and exponential expenses.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, which cites a military spokesman, the commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the flagship of the all-new frigates of Baden-Württemberg, was postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but the worrying problems that occurred after delivery compromised the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships commissioned by the Navy in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is certain that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as certain stealth technologies, such as a reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to deploy the most recent frigates for up to two years outside home ports.
According to Die Zeit, however, the incessant delays mean that the avant-garde warships - which should allow Germany to project its force overseas - will already be obsolete when they are put into service.
Last year, the cursed F125 frigate made headlines when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after its delivery.
The reasons for this return were not well known, but the German media mentioned a number of "software and hardware flaws" that made the warship unnecessary in the event of deployment on a combat mission.
Software malfunctions were particularly significant as Baden-Württemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of approximately 120 sailors, which corresponds to half of the crews of the old Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it appears that the vessel is significantly overloaded, reducing its performance and reducing the Navy's ability to make future improvements.
It is estimated that the 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz weighs twice as much as the similar class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Beyond computer system failures, the cost of the entire project - including crew training - is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached the astronomical sum of 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion dollars), compared to 2.2 billion at the beginning.
The problems related to the new frigates are particularly important in the light of recent warnings that Germany's naval force is declining.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the defence committee of the German parliament, earlier this year acknowledged that the Navy is in fact "short of ships able to deploy".
The official stated that the situation had produced a snowball effect over time, as the old vessels were downgraded but no replacement vessels were designated.
He regretted that none of the Baden-Württemberg-class frigates could join the Navy.
The National Trust monitors the secret lives of bats
New research in a Scottish Highlands domain is looking to reveal how bats use the landscape in their food quest.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
Researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will study common and sopranos pipistrelles as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton in the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable sensors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat calls and the activities of the different species.
A habitat map and report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important areas of habitat for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as grassland creation and how best to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects perches and results in habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly paper and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by pet cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, given their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to capturing prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to identify insects and obstacles on their flight route.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perch inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established the first and only reserve of Scottish bats at the Threeve site in Dumfries-et-Galloway, which houses eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, domain manager, says the site is the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Threave, we have an ideal place for bats," he says.
"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the right habitat.
But much remains to be learned about bats, so the work we do here and in other places will help us better understand what bats need to thrive."
He stressed the importance of checking the presence of bats before carrying out property maintenance, because by destroying one maternity nest without wishing, 400 females and young could be killed, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their perches.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and as far as many of our species are concerned, we don't know what's going on in their populations right now."
