The Burnaston plant - which manufactures Toyota's Auris and Avensis vehicles - built nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to other EU countries.
"I consider that if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production will stop at our plant," said Marvin Cooke, Toyota's manager in Burnaston.
Other British car manufacturers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have expressed their fear of leaving the EU without agreement on the functioning of cross-border trade.
For example, BMW indicates that it will close its Mini plant in Oxford for a month following Brexit.
The biggest concerns are what car manufacturers describe as supply chain risks in the event of Brexit without agreement.
Toyota's production line is operated in "stretched flow", parts arrive every 37 minutes from suppliers from the UK and the EU for custom-made vehicles.
If on 29 March, the UK leaves the EU without agreement, there could be disruptions at the border which, according to industry, could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to keep the inventory more than a day at its Derbyshire plant, said the company, and therefore production would be stopped.
