Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty if they buy a property in the United Kingdom
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher stamp duties if they buy a property in the UK and extra money will be used to help the homeless under the new conservative regimes
This will reverse Corbyn's successful campaign to attract young voters
The increase in stamp duty will be imposed on those who do not pay taxes in the United Kingdom
The Treasury expects to collect up to £120 million Sterling a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty rate if they buy a property in the UK - the extra money will be used to help the homeless, Theresa May will announce today.
This will be seen as an initiative to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn's campaign to attract young voters by committing to providing more affordable housing and targeting people earning high incomes.
The increase in the stamp duty will be imposed on individuals and businesses that do not pay taxes in the UK, and the additional money will be used to strengthen the government's efforts to help the homeless.
