Many rich areas of the country - particularly in the capital - have become "ghost cities" because of the high number of foreign buyers who mostly stay outside the country.
This new policy comes just a few weeks after Boris Johnson demanded a reduction in stamp duty to help more young people acquire a first home.
Accusing large construction companies to keep property prices high by grabbing land without using it, he called on Ms. May to waive quotas on affordable housing with the aim of settling the "real estate disgrace" in the United Kingdom.
Mr. Corbyn presented an attractive series of reform proposals in the housing sector, including rent control and the elimination of “no-fault” evictions.
It also wishes to give the councils wider powers to build new housing.
