Red tide info update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota decreased
The latest report from the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte, and Collier counties - raising concerns about declining concentrations.
The red tide covers approximately 209 km (130 miles) of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
Islets are found about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but at fewer sites than last week.
Red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations off Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or offshore, average concentrations in Charlotte County and low concentrations in and off Lee County, high concentrations at the bottom or offshore in Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation was reported in northwestern Florida over the past week.
